At least it's 2 cost so it has some muddle synergies. Other than that this card is quite bad most of the time. The high end isn't even that much higher than normal for a carnage style card, and if you do get anywhere near the low end (12 or less damage) it's just abysmal for the cost, and will likely really cost you in that fight. Loaded die doesn't do much to help here, and pure luck is a rare that you have to draw on the same turn, so there is very little support for these dice rolling cards. I would never pick this unless I was absolutely desperate for frontloaded damage in the early game, and there will almost always be better options available for that. Snecko eye or master eye improves it significantly since the cost will often be lowered, Necronomicon can double play it. Snecko's campfire actions are already crowded with the unidentified cards, so taking this and hoping to go big in the style of searing blow is a very awkward plan, and barely even factors into my evaluation of the card. In general, I agree that these dice rolling cards as a whole are both woefully under supported, and not very fun to play with. No one wants their card to just not work half the time, especially considering that this is a form of output randomness, where you have to pay for the card before seeing what the result of the roll will be.

I honestly disagree on two of these fronts, I think the type of randomness needs to be changed. I proposed a snecko rework a month or two ago, and I will share what I said again and how it pertains to these 3 issues, those being random cards, random numbers, and random cost.

Random cards: I think keeping unidentified cards but heavily reworking them could work. My idea is that when you click to add one into your deck, instead of adding the unid'd card into your deck it gives a 3 option unskippable card pack of cards that meet the criteria and you must add one to your deck. This still keeps the flavor and unpredictability, but makes your deck have an actual sense of cohesion and consistency. You know what is in your deck, but it still has the randomness.

Random numbers: This is easy. Just make it so the numbers are random, but when the card is drawn you know what the value is before you play it. So for a 8-12 damage number, you already know exactly how much damage it will do before you play it. I'm not 100% sold on random numbers, but this will greatly alleviate it alongside probably some buffs to some of the random number cards, as a lot of them are hot garbage even if you take the average.

Random cost (muddling): This is a feature I just think needs to go. Ironically this is probably the one that current snecko leans into most, but I don't think it makes for fun, balanced, or skillful gameplay.
